<section xml:id="nonlinear02" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Hamiltonian Systems</title>
	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p> To understand that a <term>Hamiltonian system</term> is a system of the form <md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} &amp; = \frac{\partial H}{\partial y} (x, y)</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x, y),</mrow>
					</md>
					where <m>H : {\mathbb R}^2 \rightarrow {\mathbb R}^2</m> is a smooth function.
					In particular, <m>H</m> is called a <term>Hamiltonian function</term> for the
					system. </p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<p> To understand that if <md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} &amp; = \frac{\partial H}{\partial y} (x, y)</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x, y),</mrow>
					</md>
					is a Hamiltonian system, then <m>H</m> is constant along any solution curve. In
					particular, the solution curves of a Hamiltonian system are the level sets of <m>
					H</m>. </p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<p> To understand how to compute <m>H</m> for a Hamiltonian system </p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<p>
					To understand that a Hamiltonian system has no spiral sinks or sources.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p> An undamped harmonic oscillator, <m>m y'' + k y = 0</m>, can be written as the system <md>
				<mrow>y' \amp = v</mrow>
				<mrow>v' \amp = -\frac{k}{m} y.</mrow>
			</md> Now suppose that <m>(y(t),
			v(t))</m> is a solution curve in the <m>yv</m>-plane. We will calculate the slope of the
			solution curve, <m>dv/dy</m>. Using the fact from calculus that the derivative of an
			inverse function is <me>
				\frac{d}{dx} f^{-1}(x) = \frac{1}{f'(x)},
			</me> we have <me>
				\frac{dv}{dy} = \frac{dv}{dt} \cdot \frac{dt}{dy} = \frac{dv/dt}{dy/dt} = -
			\frac{ky}{mv}.
			</me>
			In general for the system <md>
				<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = f(x, y)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = g(x, y),</mrow>
			</md> we have <me>
			\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{g(x, y)}{f(x, y)}.
			</me>
		</p>

		<p> Using separation of variables to solve the equation <me>
				\frac{dv}{dy} = - \frac{ky}{mv},
			</me> we obtain the solution <men
				xml:id="nonlinear02-equation-conservation-of-energy">\frac{1}{2} m v^2 + \frac{1}{2}
			k y^2 = C,
			</men> where <m>C</m> is a constant.
			The first term of <xref ref="nonlinear02-equation-conservation-of-energy" /> is the <term>kinetic
			energy function</term> of the harmonic oscillator <me>
				K = \frac{1}{2} m v^2,
			</me> while the second term is the <term>potential energy
			function</term>
			<me>
				U = \int_0^y k s \, ds = \frac{1}{2} k y^2.
			</me> For this reason, we call the
			function <me>
				E = K + U = \frac{1}{2} m v^2 + \frac{1}{2} k y^2
			</me> the <term>total energy
			function</term> of the harmonic oscillator. Equation<nbsp /><xref
				ref="nonlinear02-equation-conservation-of-energy" /> tells us that energy is
			conserved. That is, the sum of the potential energy and the kinetic energy is constant. </p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection xml:id="nonlinear02-subsection-pendulum">
		<title>The Nonlinear Pendulum</title>
		<p> While pendulums have long been used in clocks to keep time, they have also been used to
			measure gravity as well as used in early seismometers to measure the effect of
			earthquakes. One of the more interesting uses of a pendulum has been to measure the
			rotation of the earth. In 1851, the French physicist, LÃ©on Foucault, used a pendulum (<xref
				ref="nonlinear02-figure-fouclault" />) to demonstrate that the earth actually
			rotated on its axis. The fact that the earth rotates had been known for a long time, but
			Foucault's experiment gave the first simple proof of this phenomena. </p>

		<figure xml:id="nonlinear02-figure-fouclault">
			<caption>Foucault Pendulum Clock<mdash />California Academy of Sciences</caption>
			<image width="80%" source="nonlinear02-fouclaut.jpg">
				<description>
					<p>
						a photo of the Foucault Pendulum Clock at the California Academy of Sciences
					</p>
				</description>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<!--Description
		By TheDailyNathan (Own work) [CC BY-SA 3.0 (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0)], via
		Wikimedia Commons
		-->
		<p> Let us consider a pendulum made of a light rod of length <m>L</m> called the <term>arm</term>
			of the pendulum with a mass <m>m</m> on the end of the rod called the <term>bob</term> (<xref
				ref="nonlinear02-figure-pendulum-1" />). We will ignore the mass of the arm in our
			system. The position of the bob is given by <m>\theta(t)</m>, which we will measure in a
			counterclockwise direction. We will assume that <m>\theta(0)</m> is when the bob is in
			the vertical position. </p>

		<figure xml:id="nonlinear02-figure-pendulum-1">
			<caption>The nonlinear pendulum</caption>
			<image width="40%" xml:id="nonlinear02-pendulum-1">
				<description>
					<p>
						a diagram of a pendulum with an arm of length L and displacement of theta
						and a bob of mass m
					</p>
				</description>
				<!-- Replaced figure with tikz figure - TWJ 6/11/2010 -->
				<latex-image><![CDATA[
				\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
				\draw[very thick] (0,-0.5) -- ++(90:5) -- ++(300:4.5) ++(300:0.5) coordinate(BOB) node {$m$};
				\draw[very thick] (BOB) circle (0.5);
				\draw[dashed] (0,0.25) arc (270:300:3.75);
				\draw[thin,->] (0,3.5) arc (270:300:1);
				\node at (2,3) {$L$};
				\node at (0.35,3) {$\theta$};
				\draw (-4,1)  (5,1);
				\end{tikzpicture}]]>
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p> There are two forces acting on the pendulum<mdash />gravity and friction. The position
			of the bob at time <m>t</m> is <me>
				(L \sin \theta(t), - L \cos \theta(t)),
			</me> and the velocity of the bob is <m>L
			(d \theta / dt)</m>, the length of the velocity vector (<xref
				ref="nonlinear02-figure-pendulum-2" />). The component of the acceleration that
			points along the direction of motion of the bob is <me>
				L \frac{d^2 \theta}{dt^2}.
			</me> We can take the force due to friction to be
			proportional to the velocity, <me>
				- b L \frac{d \theta}{dt},
			</me> where <m>b \geq 0</m>. Thus, Newton's second
			law tells us that <me>
				m L \frac{d^2 \theta}{dt^2} = -b L \frac{d \theta}{dt} - mg \sin \theta
			</me> or <me>
			\frac{d^2 \theta}{dt^2} + \frac{b}{m} \frac{d \theta}{dt} + \frac{g}{L} \sin \theta = 0.
			</me>
			As a system, we can model the pendulum as <md>
				<mrow>\frac{d \theta}{dt} \amp = v</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dv}{dt} \amp = - \frac{b}{m} v - \frac{g}{L} \sin \theta.</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="nonlinear02-figure-pendulum-2">
			<caption>Forces on the nonlinear pendulum</caption>
			<image width="60%" xml:id="nonlinear02-pendulum-2">
				<description>
