				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p> If there is no damping for our pendulum, we say that we have an <term>ideal pendulum</term>.
			In this case, <md>
				<mrow>\frac{d \theta}{dt} \amp = v</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dv}{dt} \amp = - \frac{g}{L} \sin \theta.</mrow>
			</md> Since <me>
			\frac{dv}{d \theta} = - \frac{g \sin \theta}{Lv},
			</me> we know that the energy
			function for the pendulum is <me>
				E(\theta, v) = \frac{1}{2} v^2 - \frac{g}{L} \cos \theta.
			</me> Of course, <m>E(\theta,
			v)</m> is constant on the ideal pendulum. </p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="nonlinear02-subsection-hamiltonian-systems">
		<title>Hamiltonian Systems</title>
		<p> The ideal pendulum and the undamped harmonic oscillator are examples of Hamiltonian
			systems. More specifically, a <term>Hamiltonian system</term> is a system of the form <md>
				<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial H}{\partial y} (x, y)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x, y),</mrow>
			</md>
			where <m>H : {\mathbb R}^2 \rightarrow {\mathbb R}</m> is a smooth function. </p>

		<example xml:id="nonlinear02-example-hamilitonian-1">
			<p> The system <md>
					<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = -2x - 3y^2</mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -3x^2 + 2y</mrow>
				</md> is Hamiltonian
				since for <m>H(x, y) = x^3 - 2xy - y^3</m>
				<md>
					<mrow>\frac{\partial H}{\partial y} \amp = -2x - 3y^2</mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{\partial H}{\partial x} \amp = -(-3x^2 + 2y).</mrow>
				</md>
			</p>
		</example>

		<example>
			<p> In the case of the harmonic oscillator and ideal pendulum, <m>H</m> is just the
				energy function. For the harmonic oscillator, the Hamiltonian function is <me>
					E = K + U = \frac{1}{2} m v^2 + \frac{1}{2} k y^2.
				</me> In this case, <md>
					<mrow>\frac{\partial E}{\partial v} \amp = y' = mv</mrow>
					<mrow>-\frac{\partial E}{\partial y} \amp = v' = -k y.</mrow>
				</md>
				A change of variables (<m>y = my</m>) tells us that this system is equivalent to the
				system <md>
					<mrow>y' \amp = v</mrow>
					<mrow>v' \amp = -\frac{k}{m} y.</mrow>
				</md>
			</p>

			<p> For the ideal pendulum <md>
					<mrow>\frac{\partial E}{\partial v} \amp =\frac{d \theta}{dt} = v</mrow>
					<mrow>-\frac{\partial E}{\partial \theta} \amp =\frac{dv}{dt} = - \frac{g}{L}
				\sin \theta,</mrow>
				</md> where <me>
					E(\theta, v) = \frac{1}{2} v^2 - \frac{g}{L} \cos \theta.
				</me>
			</p>
		</example>

		<p>
			The following theorem tells the importance of Hamiltonian systems.
			That is, the solution curves of the system are simply the level sets of the Hamiltonian
			function.
		</p>

		<theorem xml:id="nonlinear02-theorem-hamiltonian-constant">
			<statement>
				<p> Let <md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial H}{\partial y} (x, y)</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x, y),</mrow>
					</md>
					be a Hamiltonian system, where <m>H : {\mathbb R}^2 \rightarrow {\mathbb R}</m>.
					Then <m>H</m> is constant along any solution curve. </p>
			</statement>
		</theorem>


		<proof>
			<p> Let <m>(x(t), y(t))</m> be a solution curve for the system. Using the chain rule <md>
					<mrow>\frac{dH}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial H}{\partial x} \frac{dx}{dt} +
				\frac{\partial H}{\partial y} \frac{dy}{dt}</mrow>
					<mrow>\amp = \frac{\partial H}{\partial x} \left(\frac{\partial H}{\partial y}
				\right)+ \frac{\partial H}{\partial y} \left( -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x} \right)</mrow>
					<mrow>\amp = 0.</mrow>
				</md>
			</p>
		</proof>

		<p>
			<xref ref="nonlinear02-theorem-hamiltonian-constant" /> tells us how to draw the
			solution curves in the phase plane without solving the system. Assuming that the
			Hamiltonian function <m>H</m> is not constant on any open set in <m>{\mathbb R}^2</m>,
			we simply need to plot the level curves, <m>H(x, y) = C</m>. The solutions of the system
			live on these level sets, and all we need to do is find the direction of the solution
			curve. However, this is quite easy since we know the vector field of the system.
			Furthermore, the equilibrium points of the Hamiltonian system occur at the critical
			points of <m>H</m> (where the partials of <m>H</m> vanish). For example, we can see the
			solution curves of <md>
				<mrow>\frac{\partial H}{\partial y} \amp = -2x - 3y^2</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{\partial H}{\partial x} \amp = -(-3x^2 + 2y).</mrow>
			</md> in <xref
				ref="nonlinear02-figure-hamiltonian-solutions" />. </p>

		<figure xml:id="nonlinear02-figure-hamiltonian-solutions">
			<caption>Solution curves of <m>x' = x - 3 y^2</m> and <m>y' = -y</m></caption>
			<image width="60%" xml:id="nonlinear02-hamiltonian-solutions">
				<description>
					<p>
						solution curves on a direction field of slope arrows
					</p>
				</description>
				<sageplot>
					x, y, t = var('x y t')
					xmin = -1.5
					xmax = 1.5
					ymin = -1.5
					ymax = 1.5
					f = -2*x - 3*y^2
					g = -3*x^2 + 2*y
					H(x,y) = x^3 - 2*x*y - y^3
					n = sqrt(f^2 + g^2)
					p = plot_vector_field( (f/n,g/n), (x,xmin,xmax), (y,ymin,ymax),
					axes_labels=['$x(t)$','$y(t)$'], aspect_ratio=1 )
					p += contour_plot(H, (x,xmin,xmax), (y,ymin,ymax), fill=False, cmap='hsv',
					contours=[-2, -1, 0,1, 2])
					p
				</sageplot>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="nonlinear02-subsection-ideal-pendulum">
		<title>The Ideal Pendulum Revisited</title>
		<p> The ideal pendulum <md>
				<mrow>\frac{d \theta}{dt} &amp; = v</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dv}{dt} &amp; = - \frac{g}{L} \sin \theta.</mrow>
			</md> is
			Hamiltonian, since the total energy function <men
				xml:id="nonlinear02-equation-ideal-pendulum">H(\theta, v) = E(\theta, v) =
			\frac{1}{2} v^2 - \frac{g}{L} \cos \theta.
			</men> is
			the Hamiltonian function for the system. If we set <m>g/L = 1</m>, then the solution
			curves of the system are just the level curves of <xref
				ref="nonlinear02-equation-ideal-pendulum" />. In <xref
				ref="nonlinear02-figure-ideal-pendulum" />, the closed ellipses correspond to the
			normal motion of a pendulum, while cosine curves correspond to a pendulum that always
			rotates in the same direction. The curves that join the equilibrium points correspond to
			the pendulum that rotates exactly to the top of the arc and then rotates back in the
			other direction. </p>
