		<p> Hamiltonian systems are rather rare. Given a system, we need a test to see if it is
			indeed Hamiltonian. For the system <md>
				<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} &amp; = f(x, y)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = g(x, y),</mrow>
			</md> we wish to find a
			function <m>H(x, y)</m> such that <md>
				<mrow>\frac{\partial H}{\partial y} &amp; = f(x, y)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{\partial H}{\partial x} &amp; = -g(x, y).</mrow>
			</md> If
			such a function exists, then <me>
				\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial x \partial y} =
			\frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial y \partial x} = - \frac{\partial g}{\partial y}.
			</me>
			Thus, <me>
				\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = - \frac{\partial g}{\partial y},
			</me> if our
			system is Hamiltonian. </p>

		<example>
			<p> We already know that the system <md>
					<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = -2x - 3y^2</mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -3x^2 + 2y</mrow>
				</md> is
				Hamiltonian. Indeed, <me>
					\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = - \frac{\partial g}{\partial y} = -2.
				</me>
			</p>
		</example>

		<p> The condition that <me>
				\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = - \frac{\partial g}{\partial y},
			</me> is also
			sufficient for <md>
				<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} &amp; = f(x, y)</mrow>
				<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = g(x, y),</mrow>
			</md> to be a Hamiltonian
			system. That is, we can construct a Hamiltonian function if <m>\partial f/ \partial x =
				- \partial g/ \partial y</m>. If <me>
				f(x, y) = \frac{\partial H}{\partial y}(x, y),
			</me> then <me>
				H(x, y) = \int f(x, y) \, dy + \phi(x).
			</me> Differentiating <m>H</m> with
			respect to <m>x</m>, tells us that <me>
				\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}(x, y) = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \int f(x, y) \, dy
			+ \phi'(x) = - g(x, y).
			</me>
			Now we can determine <m>\phi(x)</m> by solving the first-order differential equation <me>
			\phi'(x) = - g(x, y) - \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \int f(x, y) \, dy.
			</me> We
			summarize our results in the following theorem. </p>

		<theorem xml:id="nonlinear02-theorem-finding-hamiltonians">
			<statement>
				<p> Let <md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} &amp; = f(x, y)</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = g(x, y),</mrow>
					</md> where <m>
					f</m> and <m>g</m> are continuously differentiable. <ol>
						<li> If the system is Hamiltonian, then <men
								xml:id="nonlinear02-equation-finding-hamiltonians">\frac{\partial
					f}{\partial x} = - \frac{\partial g}{\partial y}.
							</men>
						</li>

						<li> If equation<nbsp /><xref
								ref="nonlinear02-equation-finding-hamiltonians" /> is true on a
					rectangle <m>R</m>, then the system is Hamiltonian on <m>R</m> and <me>
								H(x, y) = \int f(x, y) \, dy + \phi(x),
							</me> where <me>
					\phi'(x) = -\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left( \int f(x, y) \, dy \right) - g(x,
					y).
							</me>
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</theorem>

		<example>
			<p> As an example, we will show how we constructed the Hamiltonian function given in <xref
					ref="nonlinear02-example-hamilitonian-1" /> for the system <md>
					<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = -2x - 3y^2</mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -3x^2 + 2y</mrow>
				</md> First, <me>
				H(x, y) = \int f(x, y) \, dy + \phi(x) = \int (-2x - 3y^2) \, dy + \phi(x) = -2xy -
				y^3 + \phi(x).
				</me>
				Consequently, <md>
					<mrow>\phi'(x) \amp = - g(x, y) - \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \int f(x, y) \, dy</mrow>
					<mrow>\amp = -(-3x^2 + 2y) - \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(-2xy - y^3)</mrow>
					<mrow>\amp = 3x^2 - 2y + 2y</mrow>
					<mrow>\amp = 3x^2,</mrow>
				</md> and <m>\phi(x) = x^3 + C</m>,
				where <m>C</m> is any constant. If we choose <m>C = 0</m>, our Hamiltonian function
				is <me>
					H(x, y) = -2xy - y^3 + \phi(x) = -2xy - y^3 + x^3.
				</me>
			</p>
		</example>

		<example xml:id="nonlinear02-example-finding-hamiltonians">
			<p> As a second example, suppose <md>
					<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} &amp; = -x^2 \cos y \sin x</mrow>
					<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} &amp; = x^2 \cos x \sin y + 2x(\sin x \sin y - 1).</mrow>
				</md>
				Since <me>
					\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = x^2 \cos x \cos y - 2x \cos y \sin x = -
				\frac{\partial g}{\partial y}
				</me>
				our system is Hamiltonian. To find a Hamiltonian, we compute <me>
					H(x, y) = \int f(x, y) \, dy + \phi(x) = \int (-x^2 \cos y \sin x) \, dy +
				\phi(x) = -x^2 \sin x \sin y + \phi(x).
				</me>
				Thus, <md>
					<mrow>\phi'(x) &amp; = - g(x, y) - \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \int f(x, y) \,
						dy</mrow>
					<mrow>&amp; = -(x^2 \cos x \sin y + 2x(\sin x \sin y - 1)) - ( 2x \sin x \sin y
						- x^2 \cos x \sin y)</mrow>
					<mrow>&amp; = 2x,</mrow>
				</md> and <m>\phi(x) = x^2 + C</m>.
				Letting <m>C = 0</m>, our Hamiltonian function is <me>
					H(x, y) = x^2 - x^2 \sin x \sin y = x^2(1 - \sin x \sin y).
				</me> Solution
				curves for this system are given in <xref
					ref="nonlinear02-figure-finding-hamiltonians" />. </p>

			<figure xml:id="nonlinear02-figure-finding-hamiltonians">
				<caption>Solution curves for <xref ref="nonlinear02-example-finding-hamiltonians" /></caption>
				<image width="60%" xml:id="nonlinear02-finding-hamiltonians">
					<description>
						<p>
							solution curves as level sets on a direction field of slope arrows
						</p>
					</description>
					<sageplot>
						x, y, t = var('x y t')
						xmin = -6
						xmax = 6
						ymin = -6
						ymax = 6
						H(x,y) = x^2*(1 - sin(x)*sin(y))
						f = diff(H,y)
						g = -diff(H,x)
						n = sqrt(f^2 + g^2)
						p = plot_vector_field( (f/n,g/n), (x,xmin,xmax), (y,ymin,ymax),
						axes_labels=['$x(t)$','$y(t)$'],aspect_ratio=1)
						p += contour_plot(H, (x,xmin,xmax), (y,ymin,ymax), fill=False, cmap='hsv',
						contours=[-1,-0.5, -0.1, 0,0.1, 0.5, 1,3, 6, 9])
						p
					</sageplot>
				</image>
			</figure>
		</example>

